**Algorithms and Techniques**

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Our solution is to use CNN to help us predict the right classification of presented image we have to extract NID number area from image (using computer vision ) after enter the NID image as input then we will perform image processing on NID image part which helps us remove noise, lighting issues, etc.. also we will use computer vision to extract each number individually after threshold the image to convert the gray image to binary image then find each continues neighborhood black pixel (contours) then consider it as number and extract its corresponding area ,

at this point we have each number from NID individually this number will be sent to our CNN modal to predict its corresponding class (digit).

We used image processing technique to extract NID numbers using OpenCV

first i assume that i will have image of NID without any additional pixels just the NID rectangle image,

then i will cut it as template cut which will help me extract NID number part then image processing will start working

we will convert the NID number part to gray color then will cluster the colors to two clusters that helps us to extract black color from the image this black color is the NID number then we will do thresholding process to generate binary image after that contour function will extract each number alone then we will enter each extracted number to our CNN modal to tell us which class this number belong to .

## Methodology

**Data Preprocessing**

-----------------------------------

as per we need (64, 64) width , height on gray image that has one channel, for each number alone  and the system input is NID image we need to run preprocessing task to extract this numbers this tasks is as follow :

1. we expected to have the NID card image without any padding or any spaces between the card border or the image border.
2. we then have the card dimensions and we already have the static place for NID number place So we will cut it as template cut.
3. now we have the NID numbers image --figure - 4--, the next step is to extract each number alone to feed it to the CNN model.
4. at this step we will start working with computer vision Techniques its steps as follow:
  1. convert the image to gray image
  2. use median blur into whitening function to remove any gradient shadow or bad lighting  effect
  3. then create KMean to cluster the image color to 2 clusters black and any color other black
  4. then use threshold function to threshold the image binary black or white
  5. also using contour function will tell us where is each number individually
  6. the last step in data preparation is to use this coordinates to cut 64 x 64 box and the number is in the center of the box from the main NID image as gray channel
  7.
g.then feed that extracted number image to the CNN model

**Implementation**

We here implemented normal Deep Learning project by CNN algorithmes but we used some tips and tricks to reach high accuracy.

DataSet Step:

--

We used data augmentation techniques to generate training data from an existing dataset. Image Augmentation is the process of taking images that are already in a training dataset and manipulating them to create many altered versions of the same image. This both provides more images to train on, but can also help expose our classifier to a wider variety of lighting and coloring situations so as to make our classifier more robust. Here are some examples of different augmentations from the [imgaug](https://github.com/aleju/imgaug) library.


[figure-5-  https://github.com/aleju/imgaug](https://github.com/aleju/imgaug)

To have variety of image augmentation -Keras augmentation does not have all data augmentation methods ex. blur,brightness..

We used imgaug python library it has wide range of data augmentation methods which helps us reach our goals.

We multiply our datasets by 16 time each time have the same image but with random augmentation.

Then we used Keras image augmentation.

Augmenting our image data with keras is dead simple. A shout out to Jason Brownlee who provides a [great tutorial](http://machinelearningmastery.com/image-augmentation-deep-learning-keras/) on this. First we need to create an image generator by calling the ImageDataGenerator() function and pass it a list of parameters describing the alterations that we want it to perform on the images. We will then call the fit() function on our image generator which will apply the changes to the images batch by batch. By default, the modifications will be applied randomly, so not every image will be changed every time. [3]

CNN Step :

---

Our CNN algorithm consists of several convolution (CNV) operations followed of the image sequentially which is followed by pooling operation (PL) to generate the neurons feed into flatten operation (FL) to fully connected (FC) layer.

This fully connected (FC) layer has 3 layers each layer followed by batchNormalization and dropout to reduces the occurrence of overfitting  then the output layer with &#39;softmax&#39; activation function.

Input: of CNV is typically 2D image data with gray channel. shape ⇒  (n, 64, 64, 1)

Convolutional Layer (CNV Layer): Convolution, in general, is an operation of filtering the input data. In image recognition context, 2D filters are used to process data at different layer to generate the features. These filters are pre-defined and their coefficients are computed during training (which is described later). Basically, training is done through backpropagation algorithm with gradient descent [4].

After tried some hyperparameters and found the best for our model is to send the image in gray channel.

because all our input object will be in black color so no need for RGB to simplify the classification processes.

Also we used 32 filter for first CNV then 64 filter for second CNV then 128 filter for third CNV layer,  with kernel (3,3) this increases the accuracy of our model.

Also we used Batchnormalization() and Dropout(0.4))  to solve the overfitting issue.
